### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Bill is stuck in marsh when a man comes up to him peaking Cajun, where is he? Choices:  A: low lands B: new york C: forest D: louisiana E: everglades<n>Output:		c<n><n>Input: Bill was sitting on a toad stool. Then he got in the pool filled it with 5 gallons of water. He got out covered in goose bumps. Then he went to the party. The pool held what amount of water?<n>Output: 6 gallons <n><n>Input: On Tuesday, I am having lunch at the deli near the store at 68th street. I will go to the deli. I shall buy cheese. Next I shall eat it. Where will I get it?<n>Output: I will not get it.<n><n>Input: I have a brother. He has a brother. How is he related with my brother?<n>Output: My brother's brother is my brother's brother<n><n><n>### ANSWER:<n><n>```python<n>#Instructions:<n>import re<n><n>word = input('Enter English Words: ')<n><n>print(re.findall(r'[A-Za-z]', word))<n>print(re.search(r'[Aa-Zz]').group())<n>print(re.sub('[A-Za]', word, '', 999))<n>```<n><n>***Output:***<n>Enter English Words:  Tapanga has 100 candies and Corey has 92 candies. But if statement1 returns false then it will get into the else block which will execute the statement2.<n><n>### The output of this program is mentioned and shown below<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:The man was eating lunch, but rushed when he looked at his watch, why did he rush? Choices:  A: gain weight B: late for work C: heartburn D: bad breath E: early for work<n>Output:		E<n><n>Input:Gavin has just a ton of fish sticks, a ton of ice cream, a ton of gummy worms, and $1321.37. He decides to buy a ton of cereal if and only if $1321 remains. How does he feel after his grocery shopping trip? Choices: A: happy B: hungry C: sad D: sick E: rich<n>Output:B<n><n>Input:A man's age 3 years ago was four times the age his daughter will be in 5 years. What is his daughter's age?<n>Output: 4<n><n>Input:Kimball ran 16 laps around the track. Then he ran 21 laps around the track a second time. How many laps did he run around the track in total?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input:If you had one apple and Eve had one apple and they both started with one apple, what would you have?<n>Output: Two apples<n>```<n><n># Solution 1<n><n>```python<n>def solution(testcase):<n>    s = testcase.split(' ')<n>    try:<n>        age = int(s[0])<n>    except ValueError:<n>        return '0'<n>    return str(age)<n>```<n><n>```<n>Input:5<n>Output:5<n>```<n><n>## Solution 2<n><n>```python<n>a=input("")<n>c="".join([(t[0] if t[1]=="L" else t[1]) for t in zip(a,''.join(input()))[::-1]])<n>p=c.find("L")<n>if p!=-1 :<n>    print(p)<n>else:<n>    print("0")<n>```<n><n>```Input:appleeve"<n>Output:2<n>```<n><n># Tests<n>```Input<n>appleeve<n>0<n>apple<n>16<n>Gavin<n>D<n>```
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:The evacuation became mandatory, so what came on the TV? Choices:  A: advisory B: mandate C: soap opera D: elective E: optional<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input:The doctor's advice is that you need to what? Choices: A: have a bite B: have a fight C: have a dance D: have an ice E: have a drink<n>Output:D<n><n>```python<n>import  re<n>def answer4():<n>    d={'29':True,'10':True,'B':True,'D':True}<n>    s=input()<n>    for item in s.split():<n>        if d.get(item): return True<n>    else: return False<n><n>def answer():<n>    if False: return print(f'The answer is B!')<n><n>answer()<n>answer4()<n>```

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:She loved buying products, she was driven by her what to shop more than any practical needs? Choices:  A: desire B: money C: time D: credit E: spending money<n>Output:		B<n>'''<n>#!/bin/python3<n><n>import os<n>import unittest<n>import sys<n><n>#<n>class Solution:<n><n>    def multiple_choice(self, Q):<n>        A = [12, 7, -5, 19, 21, 15, 100, 10, 0]<n>        B_A = [10, 13, 30, 40, 50, 60, -30, -40, -50]<n>        C = [10, -300, 300, -40]<n>        D_C = [5, -3, 4, -4]<n>        E = [12, -500, -5000, 0] # Avoid negative<n>        F = [1000, -10, 0, 0, -1000] # Avoid negatives<n>        F1 = [] + [0]*6 # Avoid negatives, since it'll be used in a summation<n>        F2 = [] + [0, 0,0]<n><n>        for i in A:<n>            F1.append(i)<n>            F2.append(abs(F1[-1]))<n>            F1.pop()<n>            F2.pop()<n>        A = [F1, F2] # This is the answer that we need<n>        for i, o in enumerate(sorted(list(zip(Q, A)))): # For each input, go through the zip and find the minimum length of the two answer lists<n>            for x in B_A:<n>                if i == 2: # D<n>                    if i not in [[2, 2], [2, 3]]: # No summation needed<n>                        if x >= 0: # D can only be positive (since it's for the second answer)<n>                            if x > F[0]:<n>                                o = D<n>                else:<n>                    if i == 1: # C<n>                        if o[0] >= 0:<n>                            if o[0] > F[0]: o = C<n>                    else: # E or F<n>                        if o >= F[0]:<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:WHat do cats get into when they are ripping things apart? Choices:  A: dog's mouth B: floor C: garage D: trouble E: nature<n>Output:		Cat's in  trouble?<n><n>Input:  What letter is in cow? Choices: a: cow b: cow c: cow d: cow e: cow<n>Output: A cow or maybe a heifer<n><n>Input: What is your favorite icecream flavor?<n>Output: Caramel swirl<n><n>### Solution <n>```python<n>def readInput():<n>  input =''<n>  questions = []<n>  for x in range(20):<n>    input = input = str(input)<n>    questions.append(input.split(')'))<n>    input = readline().lower()<n>  return questions, input<n><n><n>def findAnswers(input, questions):<n>  answers = {}<n>  for number, q in enumerate(questions): <n>    if number == 0: q = '('+q+')'<n>    q = input.split(':')<n>    q = tuple(''.join(q))<n>    q = q[0].split('?')<n>    q = q[-1]<n>    print(q)<n>    temp = q.strip().split()<n>    temp = temp[-1].replace(' ', '')<n>    temp = temp.strip()<n>    q = tuple(temp)<n>    q = tuple()<n>    answers[q] = number<n>  return answers<n>  <n><n>def formatOutput(output):<n>  answerLine = ''<n>  splitLine = False<n>  outputStrs = []<n>  for y in output:<n>    answerLine += (y+splitLine)<n>    splitLine =''<n>  return answerLine<n><n><n>def answerQuestions(input, q, answers):<n>  output = [] <n>  for a, temp in enumerate(answers):<n>    q = temp.replace(')', ',')<n>    answer = q[1:].strip().split()<n><n>    output.append(formatOutput(answer))<n>  return output<n><n>with open('questions/input.txt') as file:<n>  input, fileIn = readInput()<n>with open('questions.txt') as file2:<n>  questions, fileIn2 = readInput()<n>answers = findAnswers(fileIn2, questions)<n>output = answerQuestions(fileIn, answers, input)<n>with open('output.txt', 'w') as file

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where would you find a bee gathering pollen? Choices:  A: united states B: sky C: court D: field of flowers E: orchard<n>Output:		F <n><n>Input: How many letters are in "Happy Year 2017!"?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: A man jumps from a 1000 ft cliff and he lands on his feet in 10 seconds. How fast is he falling or how fast is he moving?<n>Output: 36.5 miles per hour<n><n>### Solution:<n>```ruby<n>def solve(question, answer)<n>  puts "#{question.match(/\d{3}/)[0].to_i} #{answer.match(/^\w+$/)[0]} #{answer.match(/\d+$/)[0]}"<n>end<n><n>solve("Tapanga and Corey", "29")<n><n>solve("he calls his dad", "50")<n><n>solve(85, "10.6")<n><n>solve('"Happy Year 2", "44")<n><n>solve(-9.81, "36.5")<n>```<n><n>### Results:<n><n>| QUESTION | ANSWER |<n>| :----: | :----: |<n>| 66 candies | 29 <n>| <n>| calls his family | 10 <n>| Happy Year 2015 | 44 cents <n>| jumps from | 36.5 mph

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:If I had a jar which was likely to spoil if left out, where would I want to put it? Choices:  A: kitchen cupboard B: pantry C: grocery store D: pantry E: refrigerator<n>Output:		pantry<n><n>Solutin: There is a lot of guessing going in this question, as there will be in most questions with "What's your favorite...?" in them. A good strategy is to list a few possibilities (usually four or five, the maximum in a multiple-choice question), and then to ask yourself whether any seem suspiciously similar. In this case, the three most similar choices are refrigerator, pantry, and grocery store. The others — kitchen cupboard and pantry — are unlikely.<n><n>A refrigerator and pantry both seem likely storage places, so what's the difference? Your refrigerator stores things that need to be cold to spoil, like milk, eggs, and butter. This jar stores things that will spoil if left out. <n><n>```python<n># Answer the first question<n>candy = 66<n>t = 8<n>c = 29<n><n>print(candy, c)<n><n># Answer the second question<n>father = 5<n>brother = 25<n>newYear = 45 + 31<n><n>print(newYear* 25)<n><n># Answer Question 3<n>choices = [["pantry"], ["cupboard"], ["pantry"], ["pantry"],["refrigerator"]]<n><n>print(choices[2])<n>```<n><n># Question 10<n><n>### Instruction:Write a comment describing the purpose of the following code.<n><n>```python<n>if x >= 0 and x <= 9:<n>    print("0")<n>elif x >= 10 and x <= 19:<n>    print(1)<n>else:<n>    print("You did it wrong!")<n>```<n><n>Solution: The code above would print out numbers from the first answer in list that equals the input number <n><n>```python <n>print("hi")<n>```<n><n>```<n># Write a comment describing the purpose below in plain language (no code)<n>if x>=0 and x<=9: print("0")<n> elif x>=10 and x<=19: print(1)<n> else: print("You did it Wong") or print("You did it right")<n><n>```<n><n>```python<n>print('hi')<n>```<n><n>### Instructions:Answer the question using one

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:He had done a great job with the scary decorations, they were completely what? Choices:  A: terrible B: little C: halloween D: small E: horrible<n>Output:		E<n><n>Answer = (i) = A = terrifying<n><n>This is a tricky problem. The most efficient way to find the answer A would be to read the question, and ignore the details regarding the candy.<n>\end{blockquote}<n><n>It is clear if we ignore the first line, the problem is trivial - we can easily conclude the answer is 29 since the first line has repeated words that we could guess it means "the answer is", so I would change it to below to make that more clear and avoid people getting it wrong for accidentally using such words:<n><n>\begin{blockquote}<n>The answer is A terrifying<n>\end{blockquote}.<n><n>However, if we keep the first line, then the problem is more nuanced. By assuming most people will not try reading it, the problem is impossible.<n><n>Furthermore, even if most people do know the question is very short and trivial to read but they would not read anyway but instead focus on the long context provided by the text as they are not expected, they will never see or be reminded about the actual question until they finish reading the long context.<n><n>This is also the reason why even if people still do read the question (i.e. they see the actual problem itself), they would focus on the long context because they would not know that it is a trivial problem, so they would be more likely to think it is part of the question.<n><n>\begin{itemize}<n>\item I think this is the main reason why it is better to use a simpler text to present the test question and the actual question separately (although it also serves its second goal to be clearer).<n>\item I think a better way to implement the first problem would be to have a longer context like "They were really scary, but it was not ____." while the other part like "\strong{to read}" is removed (by asking people to "Write in the blank")<n>, and have a very simple answer choice and it is very clear that this was actually the question presented because we can see its answer choices is completely related to the question.<n>\item For the second problem, I also think it would be better if we have a longer context, such as<n><n>\em{They had done a great job decorating for Halloween. The<n>decorations weren’t really<n>[What was the job of the decorators?]<n>

Choices:  A: fishing camp B: hardware store C: engine D: your spine E: sporting goods store<n>Output:		C<n><n><n><n>### Answer:Fortnite is a video game with cartoon graphics and an online arena format, which pits 100 players against each other to fight to the death in what players call a “battle royale.”<n><n>### Requirements: <n>* Your program must accept two values, N and M as input, and output an array of integers where 0 is the 1st element,..., to the Mth element, in Nth output row.<n>* N is the number of rows of output, and M is the number of values outputted in each row at a time.<n>* The output array will have one element in each row.<n>* The values stored in the output array must alternate from 0 to N-1.<n>* The first value in the row must be "0".<n>* The remaining values must be placed in ascending order.<n>* The output values must always be in pairs of 0 and N-1.<n>### Code:<n><n>class Pairwise009<n>{<n>    public static void main(String[] args) {<n>        int N = 3;<n>        int M = 2;<n>        int[][] output = new int[N][M];<n>        for(int i = 0; i < N; i++;)<n>        {<n>            output[i][0] = 0;<n>            if(N*M <= 0 || (i + 1) > N)<n>            {<n>                output[i][1] = N;<n>            }<n>            else<n>            {<n>                int temp = output[i][1];<n>                output[i+1][1] = output[i][0];<n>                output[++i][0] = temp;<n>            }<n>        }<n>    }<n>}<n>

A number n is a power of 0 if n = 0, otherwise, it is not a power of 0.<n>><n>> A positive integer is a power of two if it's equal to 1 (which is not a power of two) or twice some integer. For example, 1, 2, 4, 8,... are powers of two, 3, 5, 7,... are not.<n><n>Example<n><n>`pow_of_two(2)` should return `true`<n><n><n><n>### Solution:<n>The first line is an integer n which we are checking. Hence, an interpreter is not necessary.<n>* To select a choice from the question, we can compare all values in the question with ones in the answer, then `exit(0)` should be used to stop the execution with success.<n>* The code below implements our solution.<n><n>```python<n>class Solution:<n>    def select(self, aList):<n>        <n>        for i in range(len(aList)):<n>            if aList[i]==True:<n>                print(aList[i])<n>                exit(0)<n>```<n>### Instruction:Answer the input below.<n><n>Input: You are in charge of building an office building that must have at least four floors and must be no taller than 500 feet. The first floor must always be ground level. However, the ground is sloped, so the floor could be in the range 0 to 8, inclusive. In particular, let's say that if the floor is at a depth x, then the actual height of the office building, from the bottom to the top, is actually x + 100 - 4. The depth is the only variable that will go into the floor function. Write a function that will build the floor of the office building on each floor such that you will input a floor number and you will get back an array with all floors that will work for that particular floor. Write code to handle negative numbers.<n><n>Output: The height of the floor should be displayed using the following: floor(x), meaning that the floor of a number must be rounded to the highest integer that is lower than or equal to that number. You are guaranteed that the input will be a number between -54 and 4, inclusive, and you are guaranteed that the first part of the function will work in both Cases 1 and 2.<n>```<n><n>## Answer:<n><n>* After reading the description, it should be clear that multiple values need to be returned in our `function`.<n>* Furthermore, we need to compare the user input with a list of values in order to solve this input.<n><n>```python <n>def floor(x):<n>    if 0 <= x <= 8:<n>        return<n>```<n><n>## Solution:<n><n>* After considering above information we should now take the floor

You guess correctly!"<n>elif choice == 2:<n>    print "B1. Oh, Okay..."<n>elif choice == 4:<n>    print "That's Correct!"<n>elif choice == "a" or "A":<n>    print "A. Wrong!"<n>elif choice == ["a", "A"] or "b" or "B":<n>    print "B. Wrong!"<n>    print "B2. Oh, Okay..."  <n>elif choice == "c" or "C":<n>    print "C1. That's Correct!"<n>    print "C2. Oh, Okay!"<n>else:<n>    print "Invalid Option."<n>    continue<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. Choices:  A: expect to die B: believe in god C: stay in D: watch movies E: eat corn<n>Output:		E<n><n>In this exercise, you write a function named solve which uses a list of numbers as its input and returns one or more strings as the output. The numbers will be separated by commas. Your function should first remove any spaces at the beginning and end of the numbers and then take each string and convert it to an integer. Your function should then use the individual numbers converted from the string to answer each question. Your code should use only the built-in methods from list in python standard library.<n><n>Here is an example of the function signature.<n>def solve(input):<n><n>Here is an explanation.<n># The input is a comma separated list of numbers. Ie:<n># input = ["My name is Joe, I like eating cheese.", 12, "I am 100 pounds"]<n><n>## Solution Steps<n><n>```python<n>str = input.split()<n>str_to_num = [str(x.strip()) for x in str]<n>nums = str_to_num<n>```<n><n>```python<n>nums = nums.pop(0)<n>total_candy = " ".join(nums)<n>nums.pop(0),<n>int(total_candy),<n>print(int(total_candal))<n><n>```<n><n>## Explanation:<n><n>```python<n>def totalCandy(input):<n>    return input.pop(0)      #removes the first string of numbers<n>```<n><n>### Explanation:<n>```python<n>def NewYear(input):<n>    input = nums.pop()       #removes one of the numbers and saves it<n>    return input             #uses that number<n>    ```<n><n>### Explantion:<n>```python<n><n>def Movie(input):<n>  num_list = input[3].split()      # takes a part of the numbers from the list and converts each one into an int<n>  return num<n>```<n><n>Answer:<n>```python<n># Answer 1:<n>def totalCandy (input):<n>    return int(input)<n># Answer 2:<n>def NewYear (input):<n>    input[3].split();<n>    return<n>```<n><n>```# Answer 3:<n>def Movie (input):<n>    print(input[3][2])<n>```<n><n>## Python: The Interactive Playground<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where would you put a dictionary while you're using it? Choices:  A: library B: study area C: table D: classroom E: shelf<n>Output:		E<n>Answers<n><n>1) 3<n>2) 10<n>```python<n>import sys<n><n>'''<n>Input : Tapanga and Core y have 66 candys together. However,Tapanga has 8more candyesthan Core y. How many candys does Core y have?<n><n>Output : 29<n>'''<n>candies = [int(x) for x in raw_input().strip().split(' ')]<n>if candies[1]-candies[0] == 8:<n>    candy_coray = candies[0] + candy_coray<n>    print 29<n><n><n>'''<n>Input:Freddy is calling his familyonNew Year's Eve.He calls his dad, who stays in the same city as he, and they talk for 24 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives one the other side of the earth, and they talk for<n>      30 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cent a minute, while international calls cost 30cent a minute. How many dollars did Freddie spend calling his family onNew Year's E ve?<n><n>Output:10<n>1<n>'''<n>calls = [int(x)*((y*10)) for x in raw_inpuit().strip().split(" ") for y in range(2)]<n>if calls[0]*5 + calls[1]*5*25 == calls[0]*(5*25):<n>    print 10<n><n>'''<n>Input::Wherewould you put adictionary while you're using the dictionary?<n><n>Choices : A librry, B study area, C table, D classroom and E shelf<n><n>Output : E<n>'''<n>print 'E'<n>```<n>

Choices:  A: reverse B: backwards C: back and D: back and E: tally back<n>Output:		B<n>```<n><n>#### Solution<n><n>```bash run<n># Problem 1<n>34 29 15 39 31 37 29 37 37<n># Explanation<n>Each sequence contains 6 candies with a + sign being placed in the position of candies belonging to Tapanga.<n>We can infer a general pattern.<n>Let Tapanga = a.<n>If a is even then Corey = a/2<n>Else<n>If a is odd then Corey = a-1<n><n># Problem 2<n>The last 31 minutes is local.<n>58(45 international minutes + 5 local minutes) = 10$<n><n># Problem 3<n>Forward<n>```

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:The rowdy frat boys shouted they would have fun and do what tonight? Choices:  A: do enjoy B: get laid C: enjoyable D: work less E: enjoy living<n>Output:		D<n><n>Input:Given the following data sets:<n><n>data = (1, (2, 1, (3,) ))... (and so on)<n><n>Which of the following produces the same result as print data<n>Output:0<n><n>Input:What is this variable defined as?<n><n>x = {print 'cannot print', print(x).}<n><n>Output: 'Cannot print'<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>To do this, you just need an understanding of the code that you need to write.<n>For the first question, we have to add 66, which is the total number of candyes they have, together. Now the number of candies Tapanga has is,<n>66 + 8 = 74. Now that we know Tapanga has 74 candies, we can find how many Tapanga has left. This is: Tapanga's number of candies - Corey's number. Therefore, the entire answer is: 5 * 2.25 is 11.25 cents.<n><n>For the third question, you need to understand the answer choices and match them up to the text. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:What would you put furniture on top of? Choices:  A: roof B: room C: floor D: apartment E: neighbor's house<n>Output:		roof<n><n><n>### Question #3:<n><n>```<n><n>class Solution {<n>    public int solution(String s) {<n>        int currentNum = 0;<n>        int nextNum = (int) s.charAt(0)-'0';<n>        currentNum *= 10;<n>        currentNum += nextNum;<n>        boolean checkForNum = true;    //check for numbers<n>        for(int i=1;i<s.length();i++){<n>            int temp = i;<n>            while(s.charAt(i) == '0'){  //stilts will check for zeros in the string.<n>                temp--;  //will be negative.<n>            }<n>            temp=i;<n>            if (temp>0){<n>                temp--;<n>                int character = (int) s<n>                   .charAt(i) -"0";<n>                int finalNum = currentNum * 10;<n>                finalNum += character;   //add the number for the next int<n>                if(finalNum < 0){<n>                    checkForNum = false;  //so check if it was neg or pos.<n>                }<n>                currentNum = finalNum;<n>            }<n>            else {   //if still have zeros we add the number together until we have a string of zeros only.<n>                break;<n>            }<n>        }<n>        String onlyZeros = s.substring(temp+1);<n>        int finalNum = 0; //set to 0 since we will be using ints.<n>        for(int j=0,k=0;k<onlyZeros.length(); k++,j++) {<n>            finalNum *=10;<n>            finalNum += Integer.parseInt(onlyZeros.charAt(k)+"");<n>        }<n>        if(checkForNum == false) {<n>            return -currentNum;<n>        }<n>        else {<n>            return currentNum;<n>        }  <n>    }    <n>}<n><n>```<n><n>Test:<n><n>### Question 4:<n>What is the largest number of candies that can be made with the letters T and 7?<n><n>```<n><n>Input: T7<n>Output: 18<n><n>Input: B7<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: 105<n>Output:

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:You can read a magazine where while waiting for your transportation on rails to arrive? Choices:  A: train station B: bookstore C: newsstand D: waiting room E: airport<n>Output:		D: waiting room<n><n>```python<n>from string import maketrans, translate<n>import re<n>'''Different ways to encode characters'''<n><n>def rotate_letters(letter):<n>    lower = letter.lower()<n>    upper = letter.upper()<n>    trans = maketrans('', '', string.ascii_lowercase + string.punctuation + '&')<n>    letter1 = translate(lower, trans, upper)<n>    letter2 = translate(letter1, trans, lower)<n>    # letter2 = letter1.upper()<n>    return letter2<n><n>def encode_letter(letter):<n>    # if letter in 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ':<n>    return letter.upper()<n><n>def decode_letter(letter): <n>    # if letter == "A":<n>    #     return "a"<n>    # if letter <= "Z":<n>    #     #return letter.lower()  # not working<n>    #     # return letter - 'A'<n>    #     return letter<n>    # else:<n>    #     return -1<n>    # lower = letter.lower().replace(' ', '+').replace('\n', '+')<n>    # upper = letter.upper().replace(' ', '*').replace('\n', '-')<n>    # trans = maketrans(lower, upper)<n>    # return letter.translate(trans)<n>    punc = re.compile("[&!?'#]+", re.MULTILINE)    <n>    word = re.sub(punc, '+', letter)<n>    return re.compile("[*_]+", re.MUTILINE).sub(' ', word)<n><n>print( rotate_letters( "hELLo") )<n>print( decode_letter('+*w+n+o') )<n><n>input = ["train:station", "news:stand", "air:port", "book:store", "car:park", "waiting:room"]<n>for i in input:<n>    print(i, encode_letter(i))<n><n>```<n>***Output:***<n>```<n>HELLO<n>HELO<n>heL<n><n>aIRport<n>bookstoRE<n>newstoStand<n>carpark<n>waitingrooM<n>```<n><n>### Instruction:

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where would I put a rosebush if I did not have any containers to store it in? Choices:  A: flower garden B: garden center C: pot D: pot E: formal garden<n>Output:		E<n>Solving in Python:<n><n>```<n>import random<n><n>print("Welcome to the quiz game.")<n>questions = ["Tapanga and Corey each have 66 candys, however Tapanga has 3 times as many candies as Corey.What is the number of candys Tapanga has?","Freddy is calling his family in New Year's EVe.He called his dad the who's in the same city with him,they talked for 45 minutes and then he called his brother who's in the other side of the wolrd,and they talked for 31 minutes in total.What is the total amounts of money spent in calls?","If you have no container to store Rosebush,where is the best place to put Rosebush?"]<n>def multiple_choice(question,choices=[],attempts=3,question_count=23):<n>    attempt = 1<n>    questions[attempt-1]<n>    input(question)<n>    choices.sort(key=len)<n>    #choices.sort()<n>    print(choices)    <n>    while True:<n>        ans = input("Please choose a letter:")<n>        if ans.isdigit():<n>            ans = int(ans)<n>        else:<n>            print("Please choose a letter only")<n>        if 42 <= ans <= 60:<n>            break<n>        if not ans in choices:<n>            print("Sorry,there is not such a choice!!")<n>            attempt+=1<n>            break<n>    ques_count = 0 <n>    print(attempts)<n>    print("Congratulations, your answer is correctly!!")<n>    if attempts >=1:<n>        choice = random.choice(choices)<n>        ques_count += 1<n>        if ques_count ==question_count:#only run the code after the final question<n>            print(ques_count,ans)<n>            return ans<n>    elif ans == choice:<n>        return ans<n>    else:<n>        print("Your answer is Incorrect. You have",attempts,"attemps remaining...")<n><n>print("Let's get started!")<n>multiple_choice(random.choice(questions),choices=[],questions_count=230,attempts=3

Choices:  A: bathroom B: walkway C: use D: hair salon E: drawer<n>Output:		C: use<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the question and explain the solution.<n><n>Question: The number of years for which a certain car had been driven was three more than twice the number of years for which it had not been driven.<n><n>What is the number of years the car had been driven?<n><n>Answer: Let us represent the years by a and the number of years not driven by b. So, the number of years the vehicle had been driven is a+b<n><n>Now, a is three more than twice b:<n>a = 3(a+b)/2 + b<n>2a = 3a + 2b<n>9 = 6b<n>b = 3/9<n><n>So, a = 9/6 – b = 9/6 - 3/9 = 6<n><n>Now, a + b = 6 + 3/9 = (27 – 9)/9 = 18/9 = 2<n><n>So, the number of years for the vehicle had been driven for 2 years.<n><n>### Instructions:Answer the question and determine the solution.<n><n>There were 2,000 people at a rally. If 10% more people were men than women, what was the ratio of men to women?<n><n>Answer:<n>We need to determine how many men there was. We will solve with our previous ratio and per cent method.<n><n>For every 100 women, there will be 110 men<n>100:110<n>1/11:1<n>There are 10 men to 1 women.<n>So, from 2000, how many women?<n>2000:10 = 200<n>But, there are 10 men and 200 women. So 2000:200<n>10:2. And the answer is 2:1.<n><n>###  Instructions:Answer and justify your answer. You can use the ratio and percent method.<n><n>There are 2,500 dogs on the beach. One-fourt of them are dogs. The rest are cats. How many cats are there?<n><n>Answer :First of all :<n><n>There are 625 dogs.<n>Two dogs.

As of today, how many people are stuck lying down unable to get up?<n>Output: 9900<n>"""<n>import math<n>class Solution:<n>    def maximumAverageDissimilarity(self, A: List[List[int]]) -> int:<n>        p = dict(zip(map(set, A), range(1, len(A[0]+1))))<n>        q = {0: False}<n>        for ai, x in enumerate(A):<n>            newp, q0 = {}, {}<n>            for ai2, y in enumerate(A): <n>                if ai!= ai2:<n>                    d = abs(x[p[A[ai2]]-1] - y[p[A[ae]2]]-1)<n>                    #print(A[ai], A[ai2], p[A[ai2]], x[p[A[a2]]-1], p[A[ae] 2], y[p[Aae] 2])<n>                    newp.update({d: newp.get(d, 0) + 1 })<n>                    q[d] = q.get(d, (True, -1))[0] or ai<n>        return sum(newq.values())/(len([(v, k) for k, v in newp.items() if k==newp[k]])-1)<n><n># A[] 为 [1,2,3,...,n]<n><n><n><n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    so = Solution()<n><n>    q = [<n>            [4, 1, 3, 2, 5],<n>            [4,5,4,19,3,7]<n>    ]<n>    p = [5, 3, 18, 7, 7, 16]<n>    #print(so.maximumAverageDissimlarity(q))<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:John is a human who is in a wheelchair due to an accident.  Where would he go to get to the third floor of his apartment building? Choices:  A: space shuttle B: detroit C: stairs D: downtown E: elevator<n>Output:		E<n><n>##### Answer explanation:<n><n>* To solve this problem we should know the concept of percentage.<n><n>```<n>For Example:<n>66 candies in total Tapanga's candies = 78(percentage)<n>Corey's candies = (66 - 78) * 100 = 28(percentage) -> 28=29,<n>We obtain the value of Corey's candies.<n>------------------------------------<n> 66 candies in Tapanga's 78 candies,<n>So, Tapanga's percentage of candies = 73<n>And percentage of Corey's Candies = 27<n>We obtain the percentage using these equations:<n>Tapanga's percentage = 78 = (66 * 100)<n>Corey' percentage = 27 = (66 -78) = (66 +(78 -78 * 100<n>We can also do this by knowing the percentage system:<n>For 78 Candies --> % = ( 78*100)/80 =100%,<n>For 99 candies --> % = (99*100)/100 =100%,<n>Subtract both percentages:<n>100% -100%  = 100% - 100% = 0<n>So, If you have more candies than somebody else then you must have 100%.<n>Now if your first person's candy percentage is 73% then the other person's candy % would be:<n>100*(73/100) = 73%,<n>and percentage of Corey' Candies = 23<n><n>We obtain the value for Corey's candie by solving their percentage<n><n>```<n><n>##### Conclusion:<n><n>```<n>I hope you enjoy writing C++ code for solving the above questions.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Choices:  A: front door B: newspaper C: post office D: package E: mail box<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: In the English language one word can have many spellings. Choices:  I: two words, II: one word III: different spellings IV: all of the above<n>Output: IV<n><n>Question Link:<n>[Problem Link](https://leetcode.com/submissions/details/52207721/)<n>```python<n>def findWords(self, words: List[str]) -> List[str]:<n>    words = [s.upper() for s in words]<n>    w1 = ''<n>    w2 = ''<n>    for w in words:<n>        if w == w1 or w =='' or w.isspace():<n>            w2 = w1<n><n>        elif w2 == w1 or w1 == '' or w1.isspace():<n>           w1=w2<n><n>        elif w not in ['',w1,',']:<n>            w1=w<n>        if w2 == '' or w2.isspace():<n>        	w2 = w1<n>    w1 = w1.strip()<n>    output = [w1, w2]<n>    return output<n><n>```<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:where do you typically find a trash can in the city? Choices:  A: park B: motel C: corner D: bus stop E: store front<n>Output:		 B<n><n>Input:the following statement is true: a city's culture is reflected in the public art there. Choices: True False<n>Output:  True<n><n>Input: what is your favorite book?<n>  Answers for this question, one per line:<n>  Choices: [bob, and, is, the, best]<n>  Answer for this question, one word:<n>  Favorite book: Alice<n><n>```python<n>from itertools import product<n><n>in_file = "problems.txt" #Your input file<n><n>with open(in_file, "r") as in_hand:<n>    in_line = in_hand.readline()<n>    in_words = in_line.split(" ")<n><n>answers = []<n><n>ans = {} #dict of string-to-list<n><n>for w in in_words:<n>    if w not in ans:<n>        ans[w] = []<n>    ans[w].append(answers.pop(0))<n><n>def combine(ans]:<n>    ans[:] = [product(*as) for as in ans.values()]<n>```<n><n>### Input:A.D., J.D., S.D., and K.S. are each randomly assigned an eight-digit ID number by 312 (randomly assigned) when they turn eight years old. At the age of 20 years, K.S. receives a randomly selected ID number from the pool of all eight-digit ID numbers issued when K.S. was eight years old. K.S.'s new ID is 2222223. K.S. is most likely to have received a number whose last digit is<n><n>A.3<n><n>B.5<n><n>C.6<n><n>D.7<n><n>### Solution:<n>```python<n>from random import randint<n>def rnd():<n>    return randint(0,29)<n><n>def get_pool():<n>    return [rnd(),rnd(),rnd()]<n><n>def get_new_id():<n>    return sum([get_pool(),rnd()])<n>```<n><n>## Input：<n><n>An eight-digit number is written using 2 times and 3 times as follows: `2 = 22, 3 = 33,` `5 = 5

A set is a collection of unique, non-overlapping values. <n><n>2. It has the following member functions:<n><n>     - is_subset<n>     - set_union<n>     - set_intersect<n><n>### Part 1: Examples:<n><n>- set.is_subset({1,2,3,4}) and set.is_subset([1,2,3]). If it's true, print True. Otherwise, print False.<n><n>### Part II: Sets Part 2: If it's false, print True.<n><n>- <n><n>### Hint for Part II (Optional):<n><n>- Use print for test cases and return True/False for Part II.<n><n>### Hints (Optional):<n><n>This is a series of sets operations example questions.<n><n>### Instructions:<n><n>**1.** The solution must be implemented in the class set using the member functions of the set class including:<n>- is_subset<n>- set_union<n>- set_intersect<n>**2.** The sample solution is below:<n><n>```python<n>def set_intersect():<n>    return set((a*a) for a in range(2, int(input("Please enter a set"))))<n>input = "Please enter three sets:"<n>def run_operation():<n>    set_set_1 = set()<n>    set_set = set()<n>    for input_set_1 in range(3, int(input)):<n>        set_1 = float(input())<n>        set_1[:-1].sort()<n>        set_set_1 -= [set_1[:-1]]<n>        set_set.update(set_1[:-2])<n>    set_set.intersection(set_set_1)<n>    print(set_set)<n>run_operation()<n>```<n><n>### HINT for Part 1:<n><n>```python <n>1111<n>111111<n>222233<n>111133<n>321<n>```<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:What city in the middle east is known for a temple? Choices:  A: jerusalem B: texas C: middle east D: china E: india<n>Output:		A.Jerusalem<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>### Approach One:<n><n>def countNumbers1(a):<n>    count = 0<n>    count = count if count > 0 else 0<n>    return count<n><n>def countNumbers2(a):<n>    number = 0<n>    for d in a:<n>        number += d<n>        print(number)<n>    return number<n><n>def countNumbers3(a):<n>    sum = 0<n>    print(a)<n>    for d in range(len(a)):<n>        sum += a[d]<n>    return sum<n><n>inputStr = input("Input: ")<n><n>a = inputStr.split()<n><n>number = countNumbers(a)<n><n>print(str(number))<n><n>### Approch Two:  <n><n>def countNumbers(a: List[int]) -> int:<n>    max = 0<n>    min = 0<n>    ans = 0<n>    length = len(a)<n>    sum = 1<n>    for i in range(length):<n>        sum += a<n>        sum += ans<n>        if max:<n>            max -= min<n>        ans = sum<n>    if max:<n>        max -= min<n>    else:<n>        max -= ans<n>    print(str(ans))<n>    return sum<n># print(ans)<n><n>input = input("Input:")<n><n>inputlist = input.split()<n><n>input = list(input)<n><n>number = countNumber(inputlist)<n><n>print(sum)<n><n>### Final code:<n><n>def countNumber(inputlist: List[int]):<n>    size = len(inputlist)<n>    ans = inputlist[1]<n>    start = 0<n>    if 'A' in inputlist:<n>        start += 1<n>    if 'B' in inputlist:   <n>        start += 2<n>    if 'C' in inputlist:      <n>        start += 4<n>    if 'D' in inputlist:       <n>        start += 8<n>    if 'E' in inputlist:        <n>        start += 32<n>    return start + ans<n>    # return start + ans<n><n># input = input("input: ")<n><n># inputlist = input.split(' ')<n><n># input = list(input) #

For example, *if* I give you<n>the numbers *"71913," *or the numbers *"13947"*, *you* may be tempted<n>to answer with *"13479."* *This* would be a mistake.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:When a monkey is taken away from their home they are often brought to this place where people wear white coats. Choices:  A: rain forest B: research laboratory C: cage D: treetops E: south africa<n>Output:		D<n><n>##### Commentary<n><n>**_Question 1_**<n><n>The total candies is $66 + 8 = 74$.<n><n>Hence the candies that Tapanga has are $74 - 29 = 45$.<n><n>Hence $45 - 29 =6$.<n><n>**_Question_** **_2_**<n><n>**_Question3_**<n><n>**Question4**<n><n>```python<n>"""DQ01: Write a python script that prints the number of <n>lines in our "README.md" file."""<n>```<n>* Output: 7<n><n>**Question5**<n><n>```python <n>"""DQ2: Print the first 5 of the last line of the file "dos.py" """<n>```<n>* Output :<n>```Python3<n>    # DQ3: Print out your name, a colon, the number 1-6 of questions you have answered, <n>    # another colon, and the number of your <n>    # question you were assigned.<n>        print("Name:", "Questions:", ':)', 'Questions:', 'Q1')<n>```<n>* Output of my name and the number Q1 question is assigned.<n>* Question 6<n>

It should be 5<n>- How to generate these questions?<n> - Use choices for multiple-choice questions (see link)<n> - Choices can be stored in a list to iterate and format them<n> - Use format() to print the question<n><n>```py<n>import random<n><n>choices = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E']<n><n>QUESTIONS = [<n>    'Your mother has 40 cookies and 70 bananas. '<n>        'How many pieces of food does she have? ',<n>    'Your sister is calling on her birthday. '<n>        'She calls her cat and talks the whole hour. '<n>        'What do you get to hear? ',<n>    'You take a plane in the morning and land on a small island. '<n>        'You are there for a week. '<n>        'Can you grow to be 7 feet tall during the week?',<n>    'What can happen in your brain while sleeping? ',<n>    'What can fall in your room while sleeping? ', <n>    'What can get cold in your room while sleep? ',<n>    'Pick 2 numbers: ',<n>    'Pin 2 numbers: '<n>]<n><n>for question in QUESTIONS:<n>    questions += question<n>    choices = random.choices(choices, k = 10)<n>    print(f'{question:<100}\n', end = '')<n>    for choice in choices:<n>        print('   '+ f'{choice}', end ='  \n')<n>    print(f'\nAnswer is {choices[0]}')<n><n>```<n><n>#### Answer<n><n>##### Output:<n><n>```bash<n>Your mother has 41 cookies and 59 bananas.<n>              How many pieces of food does <n>              she have?<n><n>        A. 59<n>        B.  41<n>        C.  90<n>        D. 100<n>        E. 140<n>    Answer is A<n>        <n>Your sister is calling on <n>                 her birthday. She calls her cat and

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:The circus monkey waived a white surrender flag, the conductor joked the monkey must work in the what? Choices:  A: french government B: friend's house C: zoo D: south africa E: madagascar<n>Output:		B: friend's<n><n>Input:A coworker of mine, the director, wants to be the next boss to the ______ office. Choices: A: high B: head C: hilarious D: helium<n>Output: B: head<n>```<n><n>**My Solution:**<n><n>Use the `re` module to parse the line input.<n><n>```python<n>import re<n>```<n><n>Split the input line on whitespace:<n><n>```python<n>line = line.split()<n>```<n><n>`re` is used to match a regular expression in a string.  We know that there are three question words: "what?" "how much?" "how many?".  So, in a pattern, find one that matches the first words from the previous questions.  Then find one that matches all three of them at once:<n><n>```python <n>re.match('{}(?: *[wh]at)?(?: *[hw] much)?'.format(re.escape(line[0])),line[0])<n>```<n><n>Replace the regex pattern with the word that the regex found matching.  This prints the first correct answer.<n><n>```python 				<n>answer=re.match('{}{}'.format(re.group(1), line[0]),line[0]).group(1)<n>```<n><n>Now simply loop over the remaining words.<n><n>```python    <n>for word in line[1:]:<n>    if answer == '' or not re.search(f'{answer}(?: *[wh][a?]?\em{?)',word):<n>        answer=re.search('{}{}'. format(re.group(0), word),word).group(0)<n>    print(answer)<n>```<n><n><n>**Reduced Code:**<n><n>This challenge makes assumptions about the types of questions that are in the input file. Instead of explicitly searching for the answers, we assume that the first word that we read matches the answer. We print the answer if it remains the same, otherwise we search the input line for another match.<n><n><n>```python<n>#!/bin/python<n><n>import re<n><n>line=raw_input('Answer the following question: ')<n>answer=''<n>match=re.match('([WH]at){0,1}'.$format(re.escape(' '.join

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where can you find a place to eat and places to buy items of many different kinds? Choices:  A: city B: downtown C: own house D: bar E: shopping center<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: What country does the Nile River pass through Choices:  A. China B. Africa C. Australia D. Europe E. N/A<n>Output: B<n>"""<n><n>class Solution:<n>    """2D list implementation"""<n>    <n>    def bubble_sort(self, lst1):<n>        """<n>        :type lst1: List[int]<n>        :rtype: None Do not return anything, modify lst1 in-place instead.<n>        """<n>        last_swap = False<n>        while not last_swap:<n>            last_swap = True<n>            for i in range(len(lst1)-1):<n>                if lst1[i] > lst1[i+1]:<n>                    lst1[i], lst1[i+ 1] = lst1[i+i], lst1[0]<n>                    last_swap = True # swap<n>        <n>            <n>    def maxProfit(self, prices: List[int], fees: List[int]) -> int:<n>        self.bubble_sort(prices)<n>        # for i in range(0,len(prices)):<n>        #     print(i,prices[i])<n>        <n>        <n>        # first pass: <n>        # find index(index0) where max profit occurs<n>        index0 = 0<n>        temp = 0<n>        for i in range(1, len(prices)):  # len(prices) >= 2<n>#         print(0, prices[0], prices[i])<n>            # print(i, prices[i], index0)<n>            <n>            if prices[i] > prices[index0]:<n>                index0 = i # find max profit occur<n>            else:<n>                temp = prices[index0]<n>                <n><n>                while index0 > 0 and prices[index0-1] >= prices[index0]: # decrease maxprofit by reducing stock<n>                    index0 -= 1<n>                    temp += prices[index0] # add to total profit by selling at a greater price<n>                break  # no more decreasing the index0<n>                        <n>                <n>            <n>#         print(index0, temp)<n>        <n>        return temp # return the total profit        <n>        <n>        <n>

Use enumerate to generate tuples (or tuples in tuples for options containing options)<n>3. Check if item is not in that options list<n>4. Return "None" if it is not in the list<n><n><n>def contains(item, tuple):<n>return next((tup for tup in enumerate(tuple) if tup[1] == item), None)<n><n><n>answer = contains(46, ('35',('56','76')))<n>print(answer)<n><n>'46' is not in the list, so it returns None<n><n><n><br><n><n><n><n>#### Solution 2 (More complicated)<n><n>### How It works<n>1. Choices:  A: supermarket B: water C: cellars D: soup E: grocery store<n>Output:		c<n>```<n><n>### Solve<n><n>``` Python<n><n># Python program to find the largest and smallest element from a list<n><n>import sys<n>t = sys.stdin.readline()<n>largest = -1<n>smallest = float("inf")<n>candies = {}<n>for elem in t:<n>    x,y = map(int,elem.split())<n>    candies[x,y] = candies.get(x,0)+y<n>largest = 0<n>smallest = 0<n>for num, num2 in candies.items():<n>    if num > largest : largest = num<n>    if num2 < smallest : smallest = num2<n>print(largest-smallest)<n><n>```<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where did the compassionate farmer allow the heifer to reside during her last days? Choices:  A: cattle ranch B: countryside C: grocery store D: slaughterhouse E: dairy farm<n>Output:		E<n><n>**Solution:** <n><n>For the first one, 8 is not divisible by 11, so we have to subtract the 8 from the 66, then divide by 11. There is no remainder. 66 - 8 / 11 = 6 / 11<n>6 / 11 =.545 or 29 candies for Corey. <n><n>In the second one, 45 + 31 = **76** minutes, so we can just do ($.05 * 76) = $3.80.<n><n>For the last question, we are trying to figure out how many **words** are in the paragraph. There are **52** characters total in that paragraph but because there are two spaces between each of the five words, we count only **35** words. The answer is D.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Choices:  A: fresh fruit B: wine press C: fruit basket D: fruit cocktail E: picnic basket<n>Output:		E<n><n>Input: What is a 365-year old called? A. Decade  B. Century  C. Year  D. Lifetime<n>Output: C<n><n><n>### 1.<n><n>```python<n>def chop(arr, n):<n>    if len(arr) <= n:<n>        return<n>    for i in range(n//2):<n>        arr.append(arr[0])<n>        arr.pop(0)<n>``` <n>### 2.<n>```python<n>def solve(s, m, n):<n>    money = 0<n>    for i in s:<n>        if i in '+-':<n>            sign = i<n>            continue<n>        n -= 1<n>        if not 'a-zA-Z1234567890' >=i >= 'a-zA-z12345890' or not n:<n>            sign = None<n>            if sign == '-':<n>                money -= 0.10<n>            elif sign == '+':<n>                money += 0.10            <n>    return round(money)<n>```<n><n>### 3.<n>```python<n>from collections import defaultdict<n>lst = ['a1', 'a2',... 'a10']<n>result = defaultdict(int)<n>for a in lst:<n>    for i in a:<n>        result[i] += 1<n>print(result.most_common(3))<n>```<n>### 4.<n>```python<n>result = 0<n>min_diff = + 1e9 <n>for a,b in ((0,0),(1,1)):<n>    diff = abs(a - b)<n>    result -= 1 if diff <= min_diff else 0<n>    min_diff = diff<n>```<n><n>## Instructions: Write simple functional programs.<n><n>### 5.<n>```python<n>lst = [1, 2, 3, 5, 10, 4, 6, 7, 8]<n>def my_sort(lst): <n>    result = sorted(lst, key=my_compare)<n>    return result<n>def my_compare(a,b):<n>    if a < b:<n>        return True<n>    else:<n>        return False<n>

Add to the list <n><n>```<n>    lst.append(3)<n>```<n><n>or <n><n>```<n>lst.insert(10,-5) <n>```<n><n>b. Remove items from the list<n><n>```<n>lst[1] = None or lst.pop(1)<n>```<n><n>c. Change an item in a list <n> <n>```<n>lst[-1] = 6 or lst[0] = 7<n>```<n><n>d. Reverse the order of the elements in a list <n><n>```python<n>lst = [6,5,4,3,2,1]<n>lst.reverse()<n><n>Output: [1,2,3,4,5,6] <n>```<n><n>e. Take out a slice of list <n><n>```py<n>lst[:2]<n>``` <n><n>or <n>```py<n>lst[3:7:2]<n>```<n>will take out the first two items and second element of lst, respectively<n><n>f. Get an item from a list<n><n>```py<n>elem = lst[0]<n>``` <n>This command will return the first  element of the list, which is the same as <n><n>`print(lst[0]) ` <n>g. Get a reference to a list <n><n>`item=lst` <n><n>The command will return a reference to the list, which you can use to do things with that list.<n><n>> Exercises<n><n>- Using a command that takes a slice of a list on itself, explain what it does.<n><n>- Given the list <n><n><n>```py<n>mylist = ['h', 'e', 'l', 'l', 'o'])<n>```<n><n>how would you take out the first letter of each item in list?<n><n>- Explain the differences between these three list commands:<n><n>```py<n>print(lst[3])<n>print(lst[0:3])<n>print(len(lst))<n>```<n><n>- Create a list called `l1` that stores a list of items you would like to send to your friend via text. The key is not asking something that  is very generic. Instead, it is important to ask something a little more specific but still shows that you are interested in their life a lot. For example, “Can we talk later tonight about whatever you want to talk about?” This seems pretty generic but it does not tell you or him anything about him, and it does not imply that you want to know anything about the other person. It is also very vague and leaves room for him to say that he does not want to talk to you, especially if he says something like, “We could, but I am not really into that.” Instead,  I recommend asking a question that shows a little more interest in him without seeming clingy. “Could we have a longer date next weekend that is just the two of us?” sounds more specific to him and what he wants out of this relationship  unlike the previous question. Of course, this depends upon if you are asking him out on a first date or asking him out on a second date  or more. It also depends upon if you are  on a date or not, but it is still generally true.

A sequence can contain numbers as well as letters.<n><n>Examples<n>a010 → 2  because 'a' will represent the integer 0 and '0' represents the integer 1. Choices:  A: go shopping B: generous C: earn money D: have money E: gift buyer<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input:The two cities below are _____.<n><n>Istanbul: 39,313,016<n><n>Rome: 39,911,102<n><n>Input:The largest city above has an estimated population of how many _____?<n><n>Output: 39,000,000<n><n>Input:The sum of the two largest cities above is ____?<n><n>Output:294,417,118<n><n>Input:The smallest city has a total of how many more people than the lowest city?<n><n>Output:110,000,589<n><n>Input:What is 4 - 1 - 3?<n><n>Output:6<n><n>Input:What are the three main functions of a computer? Choices:  CPU Memory Hard Drive<n>Output: CPU<n><n>Input:What were the first two U.S. presidents to have an actual vice president?<n><n>Output:Ford<n><n>Input:What was the largest empire in the 19th century?<n><n>Output:Greece<n><n>Input:Why is the U.S. nicknamed the "Land of Opportunity"?<n><n>Output:Because it has a varied work force and a good economy<n>'''<n><n>import random<n><n><n># TODO: Your goal is to use the random function to generate an answer<n># to each of the following multiple choice questions. To do this, you will want<n># to use multiple parameters in your function. The first parameter should<n># determine the type of question that you want to generate an answer for. The<n># second parameter should be the correct answer to the question. And the<n># other parameters should be your choices.<n><n>def multiple_choice(questionType,choices,correctAnswer):<n>    choice = random.choice(choices)<n>    if questionType == 'number':<n>        print('Correct: '+correctAnswer)<n>        print('Wrong:'+choice)<n>    elif questionType == 'name':<n>        print('Were you thinking of this?'+ choices[0])<n>        print('Your guess: '+choice)<n>    elif 'text' in questionType:<n>        print('Did you mean this?'+correctAnswer)<n>        #print('Your guess:'+ choice)<n>

Each bottle has a special label to indicate the quality and origin of the wine and also has a bottle number engraved on the bottom. One day, the chateau staff accidentally drop a load of $10$ bottles on the floor and break them. However, a few bottles have their labels torn and the numbers on the bottles are indistinguishable. The staff cannot tell which bottles were destroyed and which were merely damaged. The chateau staff needs to collect all the bottles and ask the wine connoisseur to rate them. The wine connoisseur would rate a wine on a scale of $0$ to 10, where $0$ represents poor quality wine and $10$ is a really good quality wine. The staff would only ask the wine connoiseur to rate bottles from chateau X. Chateau X has bottles from four different locations: A, B, C and D. The rating for wine from each location is different: A =$2$ B =$5$ C =$7.5$ D =$8$. The staff is wondering what would be the impact on the average rating of wines from Chateau $X$ if they remove all the bottles from location $B$ and $C$ and replace them with wines from location $A$ and $D$? <n><n>Let $x$ be the ratings from location A and let $y$ be the ratings from Location D. Since the staff did remove two bottles from A and D (and replace with two bottles from location B and C), we can calculate the total increase in ratings by:$$\text{Increase}=((2 \cdot 2) + (2 \cdot 2)) - ((2\cdot 10) + (2 \times 5))=4-4=0$$Therefore, the average rating for the chateau will decrease by $$0$$ since the quality of the wines from chateau X is reduced by $$0$$ and the number of bottles remains un

The sentence can be restated as "stand but I cannot run".<n><n>[Problem statement](https://leetcode.com/problems/natural-language-processing/)<n><n>#### Solution<n><n><n>```python<n><n>import pprint<n>import re<n><n>def solve(questions):<n><n>    # questions should be a list of 2 elements, each of which is a list of strings and has the format: [question, answers]<n>    #  For each question and its answers, each answer should be either "A-stand", "B-go quickly", "C-walking", "D-stand still", "E-walk slowly"<n><n>    # Implement answer choices by converting the dictionary of [answ er, index] for each answers to a list of tuples.<n>    #  Example dictionary of answers: {'A': 0, 'B': 1, 'C': 2, 'D': 3, 'E': 4}<n>    #  Outputs a list of tuples: [{'A': 0}, {'B': 1}, {'C': 2}, {'D': 3}, {'E': 4}]<n>    #  The choice for each answer should map the right index onto the answer with the correct letter.<n>    # Hint: Use.items() method on dict to create list of tuples<n>    # The dictionary of questions should not be converted as it will not be used in the problem.<n><n>    choices = {<n>        "A-stand": 0,<n>        "B-go quickly": 1,<n>        "C-walking": 2,<n>        "D-stand still": 3,<n>        "E-walk slowly": 4<n>    }<n>    answers = [(item, answers) for item in choices.items() for answers in questions[1][item]]<n><n>    # Input: Freddy is calling hi s family on New Year' s Eve. He calls hi s dad, who lives i n the s ame ci ty as hi m, and they talk for ht minu tes. Then h e calls hi s bro ther, who liv es on the other si de of the world, and the y tal k f or 31 mi ni tu tes. Loca l calls cost 5 ce n ts a mini t e

Choices:  A: working out B: sore C: get tired D: satisfaction E: falling down<n>Output:		working out<n><n>Input: What is the most common disease in the world? Choices:  a) cancer b) flu c) aids d) measles e) diabetes<n>Output: aids<n>'''<n>'''Example input, explanation, and output for above code should go here<n><n>In the first example it is given that Tapanga has 28 more candies than cory. 28+28=56<n>So the output should be 56-28= 28.<n>'''<n><n>def printTalk():<n>    print('Input: Freddy is caling his family on new years eve')<n>    print('He calls his dad, lives in the city.')<n>    print('They talk for 45 min.')<n>    print("Local calls are 5 cents/min.")<n>    print("International calls are 25 cents/min")<n>    print("How many dollars did freddy spent on new years eve?")<n><n>def printFeeling():<n>    print('A) working out')<n>    print('B) sore ')<n>    print('C) get tired')<n>    print('D) satisfaction')<n>    print('E) falling down')<n>    print("How would someone feel after doing a run?")<n><n>def inputQuestions():<n>    return input("What is the most common disease?")<n>    <n>def outputAnswers():<n>    return input(outputQuestions())<n><n>    <n>printTalk()<n>answer=inputQuestions<n>print(outputAnswers())<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input:Where would you dispose of a broken icebox? Choices:  A: antique store B: in the graveyard C: kitchen D: junk yard E: ice<n>Output:		C<n>\end{code}<n><n>Answer: The instructions ask for the \strong{shortest} code, but that does not mean no-ops. Since we have no knowledge of the actual input, the shortest code needs to check all the possibilities, and that means having to check all six options for input a-f.<n><n>Using your code as an example, it would work for input a, but it would not work for input b, because it assumes only one letter.<n><n>In this case, however, we do more than that. We can assume the input has at most three letters, and that it will never contain a digit. We can use these assumptions to write down all the possible inputs -- the \strong{union of two sets}.<n><n>We can further simplify this by using the sets A, B, C, and D as "buckets", and putting all possible inputs into one of these four buckets. Here are the buckets:<n><n>\begin{code}<n>000   001   010   011  100  101   110  111<n><n>|<n>+-------------------------+------------+----------+<n>|   A   |  B    |   C   |   D   |  Inputs   |<n>+-------------------------+------------^---|---+----------+-----+<n>|  Chooses 'A'  |  Chooses |  Chooses |   Chooses|    'a'   |  'x' | 'v' |  'A'  |<n>+---+--+---+---+---+------------+----------+----------+---------+-----------+--------+  'B'|   'b' |  'c'     |          |           |<n>| 1 |  |     |   x  |   1    |           |           |           |       0 |          |        1 |      x    |           |  'C'|   'c' |  'b' | 0 |   'B'|       |           |<n>|     |     |     x  |          |           |           |  1 |        1   |       x |           |        x    |       x    |           |           x    |           x    |<n>+---+--+    x  +---+-------+-------+----------+-----------+---------+--------+ +---------+--------x |<n>                            |<n>\end{code<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. Choices:  A: grandma B: clothing C: jewelry store D: clothes E: fabric store<n>Output:		E<n><n>## Solutions:Using Python<n>## 1. candies<n>##### First approach 1: <n>Candidates would list out all the possibilities.<n>First step: Let c1 be the number of candies that Corey has. He has 8 more candes than her, so he has 8 more candys.  <n>Second step: For the remaining candys, Tapanga has. We know that 66 - c1.<n><n>##### Second approach 2:<n>It could also use the concept of variable assignment. <n>```<n># Example of variables <n>var c1 = 29 # c1 is Corey's candes<n>var c2 = 37 # c2 is 66-c1<n>            # c2 could also be named c1 <n>print(c2) # 37<n>```<n><n>### 2. family's call<n>##### First approach: Using python variable assignment<n>Let d1 be the local dollar; and d2 be the internaional dollar.<n>Using equation, we get: <n>(45x5)+(31x25) = 10<n>So<n>d1 * 45 + d2 * 31 =10<n>Solution: d1 = 10, d2 = 0<n><n>### 3. velvet quilt<n>##### First approach<n>Since velvet is usually used in clothes. Choices:  A: water B: doctor C: spread disease D: mouth E: ear<n>Output:		mouth<n>### Explanation：<n>This question asks you to parse HTML text to extract information about the first child of every second element. The answer will be the extracted text. There are three different HTML structure possibilities:<n>```html<n><h1>Heading</h1> <n><p>Just a Paragraph</para><n><title>The heading is the first child <em>every second element</em></title><n>```<n>In the first paragraph, the heading is the first child of every element, so the answer is "Heading". In the second paragraph, there is no first child every second element, so the answer will be a blank line. In the final paragraph, the heading is not a child of any element, so the answer would be the text after "The heading is the first..."(every second element is highlighted in gray).<n><n><n>### Instruction: Answer the following multiple choice question<n><n>Input: What is a cat's favorite food? Choices:<n>```<n>A: dog B: mouse C: pizza D: fish E: catnip<n>```<n>Output: pizza<n>### Explanations:<n><n>This question asks you about the HTML elements "br" and "p," which mean line break and paragraph, respectively. These are very easy to guess if you see a blank line as the answer, because there is a "p" after the blank line and a "br" before the blank line.<n><n>### Instructions: Answer the following multiple <n><n>Input: I am 15 centimeters tall<n>Output: 15<n><n>Input: I like my grandfather because he likes me<n>Output: grandfather<n><n>Input: What two colors make blue?<n>Output: red<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Choices:  A: lie down B: run away C: bite D: keep alive E: feel pain<n>Output:		B<n>\end{blockquote}<n><n>Answer: So for the first one<n><n>You know you have 66 candys, of which the girl has 8 more than the guy does.<n><n>Let `X` be the number of candys the guy has and `Y` the number of candys by the girl.<n><n>So you can write `X + Y = 66` and `Y = X + 8`<n><n>Solve the equations<n><n>So the guy has 29 candys the girl has 45<n><n>For the second one, we know that the call to the father takes 45 minutes and that the call to the brother takes 31 minutes.<n><n>Let `T` be the time the call was and `C` the cost for calling a person from the other side of the earth, which is 25 cent per minute.<n><n>So we can express `T` as `T = 45 / 60` + `T = 31 / 60`<n><n>So we have `45` the time for the first call and the time for talking with the brother: `T = T + T`.<n><n>So we have:<n><n>`45 / 6o + 31 / 5t = 45 /5 t + 31 /5t` -> `t = 45 + 31 + 25 = 100 / 5 = 20`<n><n>So the call to the father took 45 minutes and the call to the brother took 65 minutes, so the call to the brother cost 67.50$.<n><n>The call to the father cost 3.75$ so the father has spent in all 71.25$
